      <h3 class="h3">What is SWEP?</h3>
      <p><a href="https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/housing/homelessness-and-rough-sleepers/how-we-help-rough-sleepers-city">Brighton & Hove City Council </a> opens a severe weather shelter in extreme weather conditions. The shelter is also known as SWEP (which stands for Severe Weather Emergency Protocols). It provides shelter for all rough sleepers in the city and venues are made available to meet demand.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">When is SWEP open?</h3>
      <p><a href="https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/housing/homelessness-and-rough-sleepers/how-we-help-rough-sleepers-city">Brighton & Hove City Council</a> has one of the lowest triggers in the country for opening SWEP.  The council provides information on this web page: <a href="https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/housing/homelessness-and-rough-sleepers/how-we-help-rough-sleepers-city">How we help rough sleepers page</a>.
      The trigger for opening SWEP in Brighton & Hove is when a “it feels like 0 degrees” temperature is forecast by the Met Office. Windchill factor is taken into account.
      When SWEP is triggered this information is provided to services who are able to direct people to accommodation including <a href="https://www.mungos.org/our-services/outreach-teams/">St Mungo’s</a>, <a href="https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/housing">Housing Options</a>, <a href="https://www.esfrs.org/">Fire Services</a>, <a href="https://www.sussex.police.uk/">the Police</a>, and health and social care partners.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">Can anyone who is rough sleeping go in?</h3>
      <p>Yes, there is no limit on numbers or any requirement for a local connection.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">How do you access SWEP?</h3>
      <p>If you see someone rough sleeping, please let the local authority know via Street Link or by calling 0300 500 0914 and the outreach team will seek to accommodate them.
      It is important that anyone sleeping rough is offered help as soon as possible and that the assistance offered meets their needs.  Accommodation for people on the streets is provided through referrals from organisations who understand what’s available and what support is needed. The council’s street outreach partners St Mungo’s SOS are currently working in the city seven days a week to engage with everyone rough sleeping to help support them into SWEP and also longer term safe accommodation.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">Is anyone ever turned away?</h3>
      <p>The team makes every effort to help everyone who come to SWEP. Occasionally, someone’s behaviour is a risk to themselves or others. The police are notified when they can’t let someone in or have to ask them to leave for safety reasons.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">What if the main shelter venue is full?</h3>
      <p>Additional venues are opened if this happens, people will be helped with where to go on arrival at the shelter. The SWEP system is set up to allow for all those who need shelter as an emergency measure.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">Is there a separate area for women?</h3>
      <p>There is currently no separate area for women at the main SWEP venue, however there are other locations for women and vulnerable individuals.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">Is there food available?</h3>
      <p>People will be provided with a meal, hot drinks and snacks.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">Can people take their dogs into SWEP?</h3>
      <p>Yes.</p>
      <h3 class="h3">What time is the SWEP shelter open?</h3>
      <p>SWEP accommodation is open from 7pm to 7am.</p>
